1.3201: This group exists for historical reasons and some programs won't run without it.

100.3201: All users belong to this group. Place files that all users should have access to in this group.

11.3201: The cdrom group is used to control who can access the CD-ROM.

12.3201: mailbox spool directories belong to group mail, MUA software runs setgid mail. This makes dot locking possible. Also, mailboxes must be writeable by group mail (Policy Manual, 3.1.1.1, 5.6).

18.3201: ppp- and isdn device nodes are group accessible to dialout. Include users allowed to initiate dialout in this group. This group owns the /dev/ttyS* devices and can read the /etc/wvdial.conf file

20.3201: games that store user independent high score values in /var/lib/games are sgid games

22.3201: Programs that should be able to access utmp are sgid utmp.

3.3201: This group exists for historical reasons and some programs won't run without it.

33.3201: for device nodes. Include users allowed to access these in the appropriate groups.

4.3201: Most of the log files (in /var/log) are group readable by users who belong to his group. You can add users who need to monitor such log files to this group. Note though that sometimes private information can be accidentally included in logs, like passwords when connecting via PPP over a Modem. This should not happen (the scripts that write the logs should identify these as not being echoed) but the potential for mistakes is there.

5.3201: The terminal devices with names beginning with /dev/tty are group accessible to group tty. Programs such as write and wall need access to /dev/tty and they set their group id (sgid) to tty.

6.3201: The disk device nodes are group accessible to disk so that programs that need access to them will set their group ID to be disk. This group has write access to all the raw disk devices (/dev/hd* and /dev/sd*), so assigning users to group disk is both dangerous and a security risk.

63.3201: for device nodes. Include users allowed to access sound in this group

7.3201: Jobs associated with the lp (printer) daemon (lpd) are group accessible to the lp group so that lpd can access them without being root.

9.3201: /proc/kmem is group accessible to kmem. Programs that need access are sgid kmem.
